text.tspan: Notes for industrialization:
* review the components tolerances
* have someone in the know review the analog audio performance and possible glitches
* process for calibrating or verifying each key's response curve?
* Add ESD protection on the exposed pins
* Remove the 0 ohm resistors and current measurement shunts
Workflow for enclosure design:
* export to DXF
TODO:
* update the board version number before producing
* Add pads for easy debugging, on all busses, power, and I/O pins
* Add ground plane
TODO enclosure:
* Select a larger battery, increase the charge current (up to 500mA total,
incl. 200mA max draw for the instrument), identify the resistor driving
the charge current.
Light guides:
* add some black background on the cover plate around the keys, to make the border very sharp
* set a 42°collector interface, penetrating inside the PCB
* add air gaps around the top of the keys to block light leakage
* put a coating of (reflective?), opaque paint on the inside of the case
* setup a photo box, to compare different solutions
* try with a slightly thicker cover (add a sheet of plastic of 0.5 or 1mm thickness between the PCB and cover)
for more uniform lighting. Cut a piece of PCB to adjust the LED hole position for better light distribution.
* try with a light guide/air gap
TODO PCB:
* Add thermal vias below the voltage regulators and LED drivers
* pads around R47
* Pull down(?) SR-OE to avoid flashing LEDs
* flood the comb with silkscreen
TODO hackability:
* prepare and offer a breadboardable version, with all IOs broken out but no screen and touch sensors
* break-out all possible busses and I/O pins
* make the charging current configurable with a through-hole resistor, and document it on the silkscreen
* try out printing a transparent cover.
TODO cover:
* Move the logos to the back, make them larger
* Add "Octave+" and "Octave-" signs to the 3rd/5th/7h keys
